4.2. Inserting

To insert in SQL we use INSERT INTO keywords, using JDBC we just use it in a
statement, both Statement and PreparedStatement work, but there is
another way using PreparedStatements “batch”. If we don’t use batch we
will execute the queries using executeUpdate() instead of executeQuery()
and it will return an int value as an exit code instead of a ResultSet.

int returnValue = statement.executeUpdate("INSERT INTO table (id, name,
surname) VALUES (1, `Leo`, `Ketola`)");

For the batch we first insert the values we want to insert into a data structure
and loop it while adding the batch at the end. To execute we use
executeBatch() which returns an int array of rows affected.

